<subSubSection id="B6A6AFB4AE48CF2BFF79FC5FFCABFBE1" pageId="23" pageNumber="273" type="description">
<paragraph id="FE03FC3FAE48CF2BFF79FC5FFE80FC1E" blockId="23.[151,720,871,933]" box="[151,311,907,933]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">
<figureCitation id="6687E0BAAE48CF2BFF79FC5FFE80FC1E" box="[151,311,907,933]" captionStart="FIGURES 228–247" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1860,1884]" captionTargetBox="[157,1425,191,1832]" captionTargetId="figure-16@22.[151,1436,181,1836]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 228–247. Male genitalia. 228–233―Anaceratagallia (Anaceratagallia) aciculata, 234–236―A. (A.) kungradica, 237–238―A. (A.) aciculata sensu Khatri et al., 2010, 239–240―A. (A.) seriphidii, holotype, 241–245―A. (A.) acuteangulata, 246–247―A. (Oedicora) kerzhneri. 228, 230, 232, 234, 237, 239, 241–242, 246―penis, lateral view, 229, 231, 233, 235–236, 240, 243–245―male anal collar appendage, 238―end of pygofer lobe and male anal collar appendage, 247―end of pygofer lobe. 234–236―after Dubovsky (1967), 237–238―after Khatri et al. (2010)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4398510" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4398510/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Figs. 246–247</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FE03FC3FAE48CF2BFF79FC07FCABFBE1" blockId="23.[151,1437,979,1294]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">
<emphasis id="CCC8202DAE48CF2BFF79FC07FE9EFC56" bold="true" box="[151,297,979,1005]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Description.</emphasis>
In external appearance and coloration similar to species of nominotypical subgenus. Penis stem gradually tapering towards apex, not flattened laterally, with two lateral lamellar expansions (
<figureCitation id="6687E0BAAE48CF2BFB9EFC23FB65FBA9" box="[1136,1234,1015,1042]" captionStart="FIGURES 228–247" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1860,1884]" captionTargetBox="[157,1425,191,1832]" captionTargetId="figure-16@22.[151,1436,181,1836]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 228–247. Male genitalia. 228–233―Anaceratagallia (Anaceratagallia) aciculata, 234–236―A. (A.) kungradica, 237–238―A. (A.) aciculata sensu Khatri et al., 2010, 239–240―A. (A.) seriphidii, holotype, 241–245―A. (A.) acuteangulata, 246–247―A. (Oedicora) kerzhneri. 228, 230, 232, 234, 237, 239, 241–242, 246―penis, lateral view, 229, 231, 233, 235–236, 240, 243–245―male anal collar appendage, 238―end of pygofer lobe and male anal collar appendage, 247―end of pygofer lobe. 234–236―after Dubovsky (1967), 237–238―after Khatri et al. (2010)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4398510" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4398510/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Fig. 246</figureCitation>
). Male anal collar without appendages; the latter fused with upper margin of pygofer and looks like additional tooth on pygofer lobe (
<figureCitation id="6687E0BAAE48CF2BFF4EFBEBFEB5FBE2" box="[160,258,1087,1113]" captionStart="FIGURES 228–247" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1860,1884]" captionTargetBox="[157,1425,191,1832]" captionTargetId="figure-16@22.[151,1436,181,1836]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 228–247. Male genitalia. 228–233―Anaceratagallia (Anaceratagallia) aciculata, 234–236―A. (A.) kungradica, 237–238―A. (A.) aciculata sensu Khatri et al., 2010, 239–240―A. (A.) seriphidii, holotype, 241–245―A. (A.) acuteangulata, 246–247―A. (Oedicora) kerzhneri. 228, 230, 232, 234, 237, 239, 241–242, 246―penis, lateral view, 229, 231, 233, 235–236, 240, 243–245―male anal collar appendage, 238―end of pygofer lobe and male anal collar appendage, 247―end of pygofer lobe. 234–236―after Dubovsky (1967), 237–238―after Khatri et al. (2010)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4398510" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4398510/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Fig. 247</figureCitation>
). Pygofer lobe gradually tapering towards apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B6A6AFB4AE48CF2BFF29FBB7FE58FB7E" pageId="23" pageNumber="273" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="FE03FC3FAE48CF2BFF29FBB7FB36FB19" blockId="23.[151,1437,979,1294]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">
<emphasis id="CCC8202DAE48CF2BFF29FBB7FE90FBC6" bold="true" box="[199,295,1123,1149]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Biology.</emphasis>
In Transbaikalia we collected 
<taxonomicName id="39BC87BCAE48CF2BFD91FBB7FCFCFBC6" baseAuthorityName="Emelyanov" baseAuthorityYear="1987" box="[639,843,1123,1150]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Anaceratagallia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="273" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kerzhneri" subGenus="Oe.">
<emphasis id="CCC8202DAE48CF2BFD91FBB7FD2FFBC6" box="[639,664,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">A.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="CCC8202DAE48CF2BFD46FBB0FD67FBC5" box="[680,720,1124,1150]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Oe.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="CCC8202DAE48CF2BFD0FFBB7FCFCFBC6" box="[737,843,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">kerzhneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
at the end of June on steppe slopes on 
<taxonomicName id="39BC87BCAE48CF2BFAEDFBB7FF43FB1A" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Spiraea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="23" pageNumber="273" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aquilegifolia">
<emphasis id="CCC8202DAE48CF2BFAEDFBB7FF43FB1A" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Spiraea aquilegifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="39BC87BCAE48CF2BFEEDFB53FEC4FB1A" box="[259,371,1159,1185]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="23" pageNumber="273" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Rosaceae</taxonomicName>
). According to 
<bibRefCitation id="9A2D81CEAE48CF2BFDF0FB53FD45FB1A" author="Emelyanov, A. F." box="[542,754,1159,1185]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273" pagination="22 - 30" refId="ref13251" refString="Emelyanov, A. F. (1987) New species of leafhoppers (Homoptera, Cicadina) from the Far East and Eastern Siberia. Taxonomy of insects of Siberia and the Far East of the USSR, Vladivostok, 1987, 22 - 30. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1987">Emelyanov (1987)</bibRefCitation>
, males of this species are very rare.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FE03FC3FAE48CF2BFF29FB7FFE58FB7E" blockId="23.[151,1437,979,1294]" box="[199,495,1195,1221]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">
<emphasis id="CCC8202DAE48CF2BFF29FB7FFEC5FB7E" bold="true" box="[199,370,1195,1221]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Calling signal.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B6A6AFB4AE48CF2BFF29FB1BFB60FAB5" pageId="23" pageNumber="273" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="FE03FC3FAE48CF2BFF29FB1BFB60FAB5" blockId="23.[151,1437,979,1294]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">
<emphasis id="CCC8202DAE48CF2BFF29FB1BFED6FB52" bold="true" box="[199,353,1231,1257]" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Distribution.</emphasis>
Eastern Transbaikalia (Chita Oblast, the Talacha River Valley near the confluence with the Ingoda River, 
<quantity id="394451DAAE48CF2BFECEFB27FED0FAB6" box="[288,359,1267,1293]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="23" pageNumber="273" unit="km" value="10.0">10 km</quantity>
West of Urul’ga Village; new record), Amur Oblast, 
<collectingCountry id="86ABBCAFAE48CF2BFC57FB27FB91FAB6" box="[953,1062,1267,1293]" name="Mongolia" pageId="23" pageNumber="273">Mongolia</collectingCountry>
(only females).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
